ed a philosophical tradition that includes Plato, Aristotle, Augustine, Boethius, and Aquinas; but surprisingly, the details of this legacy remain relatively unknown. In exploring this tradition of philosophical reflection on the nature of goodness, the twelve essays in this book (all but two published here for the first time) present some of the best recent historical scholarship in medieval philosophy and make available to nonspecialists an array of sophisticated treatments of issues that remain central to metaphysics and philosophical theology.The contributors, leading philosophers and scholars of medieval philosophy, represent a variety of points of view and take diverse methodological approaches. They address the works of figures from Augustine and Boethius to Suarez, Descartes, and Leibniz, but focus particularly on thirteenth-century thinkers, especially Aquinas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGood and evil. 0aMetaphysics. 0aPhilosophical theology. 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligious Studies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Metaphysics.2bisacsh1 aAertsen, Jan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGracia, Jorge J. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan, Mark D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKretzmann, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDonald, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDonald, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMann, William E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcinerny, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Thomas V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStump, Eleonore, econtr